10. navalibus spolils: the beaks of the captured ships, as seen from Dio LI. 1. 3. Other trophies of the naval battle consisting of captured ships of various sizes, from a trireme to a vessel of ten banks of oars, were apparently set up as an offering to Apollo Actiacus in connection with the enlargement of the ancient templeÍ¾ cf. Dio LI. 1. 2 Í¾ Strab. VII. 7. 6. The trophies are mentioned in an epigram of the first cen- tury, nn. Í¾ cf. Antbol. Pol. VI. 236. Neptuno ac Marti: such a double dedication might naturally follow a naval victory. No disaster resembling those in the Sicilian war had occurred to retard the move- ments at Actium3 cf. Any. 16. Shuckburgh suggests, in his note to this passage, that the dedication to Neptune was an amende bonorable for the impious etiam incito Neptuno victorianae adeptunrm of Aac. 16. 2Í¾ but sec note to page 54, line 3.
